    {
      "fullUrl": "urn:uuid:64c30e6c-5b1a-48df-aeb5-71ba4f771c3b",
      "resource": {
        "resourceType": "Communication",
        "status": "completed",
        "text": {
          "status": "generated",
          "div": "<div xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1999/xhtml\">patient-description</div>"
        },
        "category": [
          {
            "coding": [
              {
                "system": "urn:virpat:fhir:doc-type",
                "code": "patient-description"
              }
            ]
          }
        ],
        "subject": {
          "reference": "urn:uuid:11111111-1111-4111-8111-111111111111"
        },
        "payload": [
          {
            "contentString": "{patientName} is a 50-year-old man who appears well groomed and slightly overweight, with a soft abdomen and no acute distress. He comes to clinic after a routine employer-sponsored health screening showed elevated cholesterol levels. He speaks calmly and matter-of-factly, but admits he has become more concerned after several friends his age started medication for heart disease prevention. He denies chest pain, claudication, or prior stroke symptoms, and says he generally feels healthy.\n\nHe works as an operations manager for a regional shipping company, a job that keeps him at a desk for long stretches and often involves long hours, business lunches, and stress. His weekly routine leaves little room for exercise beyond occasional weekend yard work and walking the dog. He enjoys grilling, watching football, and meeting friends for beer on weekends. His diet is heavy in red meat, processed snacks, and takeout meals, though his spouse has recently encouraged healthier cooking at home.\n\nAt home, {patientName} lives with his wife and has two adult children who visit regularly. He is close to his family and describes a good support system, but says preventive healthcare has not always been a priority. He quit smoking in his late 30s after a 15-pack-year history and now drinks alcohol socially, about 1 to 2 drinks on most weekends. He sleeps about 6 hours per night and reports mild work-related stress but no major psychiatric concerns.\n\nOn examination, he has central adiposity and a mildly elevated blood pressure, but otherwise looks comfortable and functional. He is concerned because he has heard that high cholesterol can be “silent,” and he wants to avoid a heart attack like the one his father experienced. He is receptive to counseling about weight reduction, dietary changes, and regular exercise, though he worries about fitting these changes into his routine."
          }
        ]
      }
    },
    {
      "fullUrl": "urn:uuid:8fbbfb4e-4e0b-4087-85a9-f832f1310983",
      "resource": {
        "resourceType": "Communication",
        "status": "completed",
        "text": {
          "status": "generated",
          "div": "<div xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1999/xhtml\">patient-history</div>"
        },
        "category": [
          {
            "coding": [
              {
                "system": "urn:virpat:fhir:doc-type",
                "code": "patient-history"
              }
            ]
          }
        ],
        "subject": {
          "reference": "urn:uuid:11111111-1111-4111-8111-111111111111"
        },
        "payload": [
          {
            "contentString": "{patientName} has no known history of myocardial infarction, stroke, diabetes, chronic kidney disease, or hypothyroidism. He was told several years ago that his cholesterol was “borderline high,” but he did not pursue follow-up. He has overweight status, a sedentary occupation, prior tobacco exposure, and a diet high in saturated fat, all of which contribute to dyslipidaemia and elevated cardiovascular risk.\n\nHe has never been hospitalized for cardiovascular disease. Past medical history includes mild essential hypertension managed with lifestyle measures but not consistently monitored. He underwent an appendectomy in early adulthood and completed a routine screening colonoscopy in recent years. He reports no current prescription medications before this visit and no history of statin intolerance.\n\n{patientName} is allergic to penicillin, which caused a diffuse urticarial rash in childhood. He is motivated to improve his health after learning more about his family history of premature cardiovascular disease and is open to dietitian referral, weight loss efforts, and starting preventive pharmacotherapy."
          }
        ]
      }
